<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2>Maui Isthmus Thermal Effect</h2>

<p>The Maui isthmus — the low, flat valley between Haleakala and the West Maui Mountains — is the engine that drives Kanaha's wind. Understanding it is the key to predicting afternoon conditions.</p>

<h3>How It Works</h3>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Solar heating</strong> — The isthmus heats up faster than the surrounding ocean, creating a low-pressure zone over the valley</li>
  <li><strong>Sea breeze</strong> — Cool ocean air is drawn into the low pressure, creating an onshore flow that adds to existing trade winds</li>
  <li><strong>Venturi compression</strong> — The wind accelerates as it's compressed through the gap between the two mountains, focusing energy at Kanaha</li>
</ol>

<h3>Diurnal Pattern</h3>

